Introduction

The following report uses the public red wine dataset collected for the report titled Modeling wine preferences by data mining from physicochemical properties by Paulo Cortez.

The dataset consists of 1599 samples, 11 input variables which are based on physiochemical properties of the wine and 1 output variable which is the quality of the wine. The quality of the wine was based on sensory data (taste).

3 wine experts assessed and rated the quality of the wine, a score between 0 to 10 was given where 0 is very bad and 10 is very good.

This report will investigate which of these properties impacts the quality of the wine.

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of the dataset?

The dataset contains 1599 rows and 12 columns, 11 of those columns are measured properties of the wine and are continuous variables. The variable Quality is an ordinal variable. Quality is a score from 1-10 given by the wine taster. Most of the wines were given a rating of 5-6 and none of the wines in the dataset were rated 1,2, 9 or 10.

The table shows that all of the data is numerical, we have the following physicochemical properties we can use to explore the dataset. Some of the explanations for the properites were given as part of the dataset.

  • Fixed Acidity - Represents the non volatile acids in the wine
  • Volatile Acidity - Too high can results in a vinegar like taste (unpleasant)
  • Citric Acid - adds flavour to the wine
  • Residual Sugar - The sugar left after the fementation process. Large amounts are found in sweeter wines
  • Chlorides - salt content
  • Free Sulfur Dioxide - used to prevent microbial growth and prevents the wine from oxidizing
  • Density - density of the liquid. Denisity of water is 0.997 g/m3
  • pH - The acidity of the wine, lower values on the ph scale are more acidic (higher is alkaline). According to the information given with the dataset we’ll find most wines have a ph between 3-4
  • Sulphates - added to the wine to increase the sulfur dioxide gas level. Sulfur dioxide gas is an antimicrobial (agent that kills microorganisms )
  • Alcohol - The % of alcohol in the wine

What are the main features of interest in your dataset?

I’ll be exploring how some of the physicochemical properties effect quality. At this stage it is difficult to say which features are going to be the primary focus, that will become clearer during the bivariate analysis. However i’m interested in seeing how diffierent quantities of citric acid changes the perception of quality of the wine. Residual Sugar which makes the wine sweet may also have an effect.

A look into Which variables correlate with quality

The output variable (quality) is of most interest to us, we’d like to determine which properties of the wine contribute to a greater quality

There are some properties that do correlate with quality. The correlations are not strong but do stand out and are worth looking into for further analysis.

The properties that stood out against quality the most are as follows

physicochemical properties that correlate with quality positively are

  • Alcohol content (+0.476)
  • sulphate (+0.251)
  • Citric acid (+0.226)

physicochemical properties that correlate with quality negatively are

  • Volatile acidity (-3.91)

Other correlations not against quality are as follows

  • Total Sulfur Dioxide and Free Sulphur Dioxide corrlate, which isn’t unexpected as total sulfur dioxide contains free sulfur dioxide
  • Citric Acid and Fixed Acidity (0.672) - again this is expected with larger volumes of acid
  • pH with Citric Acid (-0.542) and pH with Fixed Acidity (-0.683) - again will correlate, higher acidity has a lower PH (higher Ph is more alkaline)
  • Citric Acid and Volatile Acidity (-0.552)
  • Alcohol Content and Density (-0.496)
  • Density and Residual Sugar (0.355)
  • Density and pH (-0.342)

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?

Higher alcohol content is found in wines of better quality. Alcohol also effects the density of the liquid, the more alcohol there was the less dense it became. This is because the density of alcohol is 0.789 g/m3 compared to water, which has a density of 0.997 g/m3.

Volatile acid is found much less in higher quality wines. According to the supplementary information found acetic acid, which is one of the primary volatile acids is associated with the smell and taste of vingar.

Citric acid increased with better quality wines. The supplementary information informs us that citric acid adds freshness and flavour to wines. Citric acids is added after fermentation, it added before then the yeast can convert the acid into acetic acid (Volatile). As we discoveres this is undesirable.

Higher sulphate was also seen in higher quality wines. Suphates are added to increase the suldur dioxide content which is an anti oxidant and antimicrobial. Antimicrobials are important to prevent microorganisms from proliferating in the wine.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

I found the quality of the wine increase with less acetic acid and more citric acid.

Parallel plots can show you general trends with all the variables mapped with parallel coordinate axes.

You can see some trends, such as darker colors (lower quality) have much less citric acid, higher volatile acidity. We can see lighter colors (higher quality) associated with higher sulphates and higher alcohol content.

I can also just look at the same chart but the mean of each property grouped by quality

A few more trends become easier to visualise. Lower quality wines show less sulphur dioxide, and higher quality wines show there is more SO2.Higher quality wines are less dense and have more alcohol which supports my earlier discoveries

Sulfites

The sulfites are composed of both free sulfor dioxide and the bound form of sulfur dioxide. The dataset contains the total sulfur dioxide but if we subtract the free sulfur dioxide from the total sulfur dioxide, we will be left with bound sulfur dioxide

I want to look at the relationship between the free and bound forms of sulfites. The total sulfur dioxide is a combination of free sulfur dioxide and bound sulfur dioxide. Lets see if there is a relationship between those variables

The results dont look too promising. It’s hard to tell with the graphs as there are fewer results for the extrememly low and extremely high qualities.

Free form sulfur is the sulfur dioxide not bound to any other substances. Bound has joined bonds with other substances which means it is no longer SO2. Free Sulfir dioxide is what actually contributes to minimsing microorganisms and prevents oxidation. I expected to see an increase in bound sulfur and reduced quality of wine. We can see a small relationship like this, most of the 8 rated wines are in the bottom half of the chart where there is less bound sulfur.

This probably is not the best way to test this theory, it would be better to look at the proportion/ratio of free to bound and seeing a relationship.

We don’t need the bound sulfur variable for this, we can easily construct a new chart using a % of total sulfur dioxide.

This chart is not multivariate however i’ve kept it in this section to keep the flow.

There still doesn’t seem to be any correlation.

Exploring Acid

I’d now like to investigate how quantities of acids effect the quality of the wine, I’m going to look at volatile acidity against fixed acidity and citric acid.

Looking at the comparison of volatile acidity against citric acid, we can see that lower volatile acidity and higher citric acid contributes to a better quality wine. All the low quality wines cluster in the region of high acetic acid and low citric acid

As expected, ligher colors (higher quality) seems to be on the low end of the volatile acid spectrum on the second chart. Fixed acidity however doesn’t seem to explain as much as volatile acid does.

Exploring sulphate

Sulphate is an additive which is used to increase the amount of sulfur dioxide levels. I look at sulphates compared to both alcohol and chlorides.

We’ve explored alcohol extensivley so it’s not surprising to see that more alcohol increases quality. An increase in sulphates upto a point helps, which is around 1. Beyond that it doesn’t seem to help even with increased alcohol.

There also seems to be more sulphate in the wines with less alcohol.

Most of the chlorides are clustered around 0.1, it doesn’t seem to be effected by the quantity of sulphates however.

Exploring Density

An increase in alcohol does decrease the density which is something we found earlier. Lower density and higher alcohol do contribute to a better quality

Multivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest? Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

Alcohol and density correlate strongly and impact the quality of the wine. Alcohol has a lower density than water and hence an increase in alcohol will reduce the density of the wine. However I cannot say quality of the wine is related to the increase in alcohol or the fact the alcohol changes the texture of the wine making.

The plots also strenghtened the relationship with citric acid having a positive effect on quality and volatile acid having a negative effect on the quality.

Fixed acidity didn’t impact quality as much as I expected it it. Citric acidity is classed as as fixed acid, there are also other fixed acids such as tartaric and malic. These don’t seem to have as great effect on quality as citric does.

Reflection

Out of all the variables studied, the strongest relationships were quite evident early on. Volatile acid, alcohol, citric acid sulphates seem to have the greatest impact on the quality rating of the wine.

Volatile acidity can reduce the taste the aroma of the wine. Excess acetic acid also puts the yeast under stress which ends up producing more volatile acid as a result.

Citric acid is used to add flavour to the wine, so this will make the wine taste nicer and hence get a better quality rating.

Alcohol was also found to increase the quality of the wine, it impacted the density which means the wine was less dense.

Sulphates ensure enough sulfur dioxide is present in the wine to not cause too many miroorganisms to proliferate and to ensure oxidation does not happen too early. Too much can be detected in in the flavour which is undesirable, this is possibly why there was a sudden reduction in sulphate quantity in the wine after 1.0 g/m^3.

There were some limitations in the dataset. I was interested to see the different vineyards the grapes were grown from, particularly the climate in those countries.

If wine is produced in warmer climates means the grapes become fully ripe but they contain less acidity. cooler climates tend to have more acidity. These wines produces in warmer climates usually have acid added into the wine.

However I understand the manufacturers wanted company names removed from the dataset.

Overall this was an enjoyable experience, exploring the dataset was interesting and a challenge. I had a lot of fun and it was a great way to go over some of the R code I had learnt.
